00:05:30.679 --> 00:05:40.679
But one of the questions from earlier was, are pins mainly for sharing data between users?

00:05:40.679 --> 00:05:44.679
Or can R code be shared or pinned as well?

00:05:45.679 --> 00:05:47.679
Yeah, I can probably take that one.

00:05:47.679 --> 00:05:50.679
And, Isabel, you can add any additional comments.

00:05:50.679 --> 00:05:53.679
Pins are really great for sharing typically objects.

00:05:53.679 --> 00:05:59.679
So things like data sets, models, plots, objects in R and Python.

00:05:59.679 --> 00:06:07.679
In terms of code itself, we would certainly suggest some type of version control using Git, for example,

00:06:07.679 --> 00:06:13.679
publishing your source code to GitHub, which makes it super easy to share that source code with other users.

00:06:13.679 --> 00:06:16.679
So I wouldn't necessarily say pins is a great way for sharing code.

00:06:16.679 --> 00:06:22.679
But it is a fantastic way for sharing the objects that you're creating in R and Python.

00:06:22.679 --> 00:06:24.679
Thank you.

00:06:24.679 --> 00:06:26.679
I would completely agree with that.

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:31.679
If you're looking to use the best tool for the job, I would say version control for code.

00:06:31.679 --> 00:06:36.679
And then pins for a little slice of data or not necessarily large data sets.

00:06:36.679 --> 00:06:39.679
This is not a replacement for a database.

00:06:40.679 --> 00:06:45.679
But being able to share code quickly with others, probably not for pins.

00:06:47.679 --> 00:06:51.679
So, Isabel, I know you helped me answer this question in Slido.

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:55.679
